  <h2>Why Preventative Care Is Essential</h2>
  <p>
    Pets age much faster than humans — what seems like a short time between annual visits can represent years of biological change. Regular wellness exams allow us to track your pet's health over time, catch subtle changes early, and build a relationship with you and your pet that makes every visit less stressful.
  </p>
  <p>
    Most serious conditions — from dental disease to organ dysfunction — are far easier and less costly to treat when caught early.
  </p>

  <h2>What's Included in a Wellness Visit</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comprehensive physical examination</strong> — eyes, ears, teeth, skin, coat, heart, lungs, abdomen, lymph nodes, and musculoskeletal system</li>
    <li><strong>Vaccinations</strong> — core vaccines and lifestyle-based optional vaccines, administered on a schedule appropriate for your pet's age and exposure risk</li>
    <li><strong>Parasite prevention</strong> — heartworm testing, flea and tick prevention, deworming, and intestinal parasite screening</li>
    <li><strong>Dental health assessment</strong> — early identification of tartar buildup, gum disease, or painful teeth</li>
    <li><strong>Nutritional guidance</strong> — body condition scoring and diet recommendations tailored to your pet's current stage of life</li>
    <li><strong>Bloodwork and diagnostics</strong> — baseline panels or targeted testing as appropriate for your pet's age and history</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Vaccination Schedules</h2>
  <p>
    We follow the latest AAHA and AAFP guidelines for vaccination schedules, customized to your pet's lifestyle and risk profile. Core vaccines protect against life-threatening diseases like parvovirus, distemper, and rabies. We'll discuss which additional vaccines may benefit your pet based on how they spend their time.
  </p>

  <h2>Parasite Prevention</h2>
  <p>
    Western Pennsylvania's climate supports year-round parasite pressure. Fleas, ticks, and heartworm-carrying mosquitoes are active across most of the year. We'll recommend a prevention program that fits your pet's lifestyle — whether they spend most of their time indoors or have significant outdoor exposure.
  </p>

  <h2>How Often Should Your Pet Be Seen?</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Puppies and kittens: every 3–4 weeks until the initial vaccination series is complete</li>
    <li>Adults (1–7 years): annually</li>
    <li>Seniors (7+ years for most breeds): twice yearly, or as recommended based on health status</li>
  </ul>

